Design correction — Yes/No variable type (flagged by power user):
The Yes/No variable type in Section 4.3 needs to be corrected. Yes/No implies a simple true/false abstraction but HA booleans only apply to actual HA boolean helpers. Devices report their own native states — on/off, open/closed, detected/clear, active/inactive — not yes/no.
Decision: Keep Yes/No as a variable type for actual HA boolean helpers only. For device states, the capability-driven wizard fetches and displays the real native values from HA — whatever HA reports for that specific device. No translation layer, no abstraction. The wizard already does this correctly by design. The variable type table in Section 4.3 should be updated to clarify this distinction, and any UI text that implies Yes/No covers device on/off states should be corrected.
When updating DESIGN.md for this, also check Section 6.4 conditions and Section 9 operators to make sure no operator language assumes yes/no as a device state.
Design correction — Global variables storage and access:
Section 4.1 says globals are "pushed to HA live memory" on save. This is wrong for two reasons. First, HA input helpers have a 255 character limit — too small for a Devices variable listing many entities — and are visible and editable in the HA UI by anyone. Second and more importantly, any runtime dependency on the Docker container breaks the core design principle that automations must run without PistonCore running.
Decision: When globals are saved in PistonCore, the companion writes a globals.json file to <ha_config>/pistoncore/globals.json — inside the pistoncore subfolder the companion already owns. PyScript compiled files read globals directly from this file at runtime. No Docker dependency, no input helpers, no size limits, no UI exposure risk. HA can be down for a week and restart without the Docker ever coming back — globals are still there, automations still run.
Remove all references to "push to HA live memory" from Section 4.1 and Section 19. Remove the startup sync script from Section 4.1. Remove the persistent HA notification about missing storage — replace with: if globals.json is missing when a PyScript piston tries to read it, the piston logs a plain English error and stops gracefully.
The Docker is used only for editing pistons. It is never a runtime dependency.
Also add to Section 17.3 companion setup instructions: PyScript requires allow_code_remote: true in configuration.yaml to enable the pyscript.reload service. The companion setup flow must instruct the user to add this line. Without it, deploying complex pistons will fail silently.
